text: I mean, I think in a lot of ways, it's the same thing that draws you to doing podcasts. I mean, it's sort of interesting. I mean, I'm not making the same sort of personal connections that you might be. It's like you read a lot, challenges you to fill in the holes in your knowledge. There's stuff that you thought you knew, but didn't. You learn completely new stuff. And you're always organizing your thoughts. I think organizing the stuff you know is sort of an underrated skill. A lot of people now are saying, oh, you don't need to go to college. But I think one of the great things about a college education that you don't get if you just read books on your own is you get things put into a structure, like a narrative structure. You're like, this is the way ancient Greek history related to the later Roman history. Whereas if you just read it on your own, you've got to put all that stuff together. It's much more difficult. And I think that's a really important part of learning. And I really like that. I actually kind of just like the writing aspect. I don't like the editing. I don't like doing all the graphs and putting equations in. It's kind of miserable. But occasionally I'll write a sentence. And it's just like, yeah, that's actually a really nice sentence. I like that. I mean, that's not Hemingway. But it's for me, it's good. It's like, you know, when a hacker hits a nice golf shot. It's not Tiger Woods, but they still get the thrill of doing it.
